Exploring Diabetes Data through Unsupervised Learning: PCA and Clustering Analysis

Boning Liu

12-04-2024

1 Introduction

Unsupervised learning is a versatile data science technique used to uncover hidden patterns and structures in datasets without predefined labels or target outcomes. This assignment leverages two key unsupervised learning methods: Principal Component Analysis (PCA) and Clustering.

The primary objectives of this assignment are:

  1. To explore and understand the structure of the dataset through comprehensive Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA).

  2. To reduce the dimensionality of the dataset using PCA, retaining most of the variability in the data while simplifying its complexity.

  3. To identify natural groupings or clusters within the data using clustering techniques.

1.1 Data Set

The dataset chosen for this assignment is the Diabetes Dataset, which contains information related to diabetes prediction based on a variety of medical measurements. This dataset is suitable for unsupervised learning tasks due to its size and the presence of multiple numerical variables.

Dataset Characteristics:

Source: Kaggle

Number of Observations: 768

Variables: 8 numerical variables and 1 categorical variable (Outcome)

Variables Description:

Pregnancies: Number of times the patient has been pregnant. (Numerical)

Glucose: Plasma glucose concentration after a 2-hour oral glucose tolerance test. (Numerical)

BloodPressure: Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg). (Numerical)

SkinThickness: Triceps skinfold thickness (mm). (Numerical)

Insulin: 2-hour serum insulin (mu U/ml). (Numerical)

BMI: Body mass index (weight in kg/(height in m)^2). (Numerical)

DiabetesPedigreeFunction: A function that scores the likelihood of diabetes based on family history. (Numerical)

Age: Age of the patient (years). (Numerical)

Outcome: Binary categorical variable indicating diabetes diagnosis (1 for positive, 0 for negative). (Categorical)

This dataset is well-suited for:

  1. Analyzing correlations and variability across numerical features.

  2. Applying PCA to reduce dimensionality and visualize key components.

  3. Using clustering algorithms to group similar observations and uncover hidden patterns.

Missing values represented as zeros in key variables (e.g., Glucose, BMI, Insulin) were addressed by replacing them with the mean of the respective variables. This imputation method preserves the dataset size while maintaining statistical consistency for downstream analyses.

# Replace zeros with NA for relevant columns
data_cleaned <- data %>%
  mutate(
    Glucose = ifelse(Glucose == 0, NA, Glucose),
    BloodPressure = ifelse(BloodPressure == 0, NA, BloodPressure),
    SkinThickness = ifelse(SkinThickness == 0, NA, SkinThickness),
    Insulin = ifelse(Insulin == 0, NA, Insulin),
    BMI = ifelse(BMI == 0, NA, BMI)
  )

# Impute missing values with the mean
data_imputed <- data_cleaned %>%
  mutate(
    Glucose = ifelse(is.na(Glucose), mean(Glucose, na.rm = TRUE), Glucose),
    BloodPressure = ifelse(is.na(BloodPressure), mean(BloodPressure, na.rm = TRUE), BloodPressure),
    SkinThickness = ifelse(is.na(SkinThickness), mean(SkinThickness, na.rm = TRUE), SkinThickness),
    Insulin = ifelse(is.na(Insulin), mean(Insulin, na.rm = TRUE), Insulin),
    BMI = ifelse(is.na(BMI), mean(BMI, na.rm = TRUE), BMI)
  )

# Check for remaining missing values
colSums(is.na(data_imputed))

4 PCA

# Load necessary libraries
library(ggplot2)
library(FactoMineR)
library(factoextra)

# Step 1: Standardize the data (numerical variables only)
data_scaled <- scale(data_imputed[, c("Pregnancies", "Glucose", "BloodPressure", 
                                      "SkinThickness", "Insulin", "BMI", 
                                      "DiabetesPedigreeFunction", "Age")])

# Step 2: Perform PCA
pca_result <- PCA(data_scaled, graph = FALSE)

# Step 3: Scree Plot 
fviz_screeplot(pca_result, addlabels = TRUE, 
               title = "Scree Plot: Variance Explained by Principal Components")

# Step 4: PCA Biplot
fviz_pca_var(pca_result, 
             col.var = "contrib", # Color by contributions to principal components
             gradient.cols = c("blue", "yellow", "red"),
             repel = TRUE, # Avoid overlapping text
             title = "PCA Biplot: Variable Contributions")

Scree Plot

  • The first two principal components explain 47.2% of the total variance (28.8% + 18.4%).

  • Including a third component raises the explained variance to 61.3%.

  • The first two or three components can be used for dimensionality reduction as they capture most of the variability.

PCA Biplot

  • Age and Pregnancies contribute strongly to the first principal component (Dim1).

  • BMI, SkinThickness, and Glucose are more aligned with the second principal component (Dim2).

  • DiabetesPedigreeFunction shows a distinct influence in a different direction, highlighting its unique variability.

  • The biplot reveals which variables drive the major dimensions of variability in the dataset.

5 Clustering Analysis

library(cluster)
library(factoextra)

# Step 1: Use PCA-reduced dataset (first two components)
pca_data <- pca_result$ind$coord[, 1:2] # Coordinates of the first two principal components

# Step 2: Determine the optimal number of clusters using the Elbow Method
fviz_nbclust(pca_data, kmeans, method = "wss") + 
  ggtitle("Elbow Method for Optimal Clusters")

# Step 3: Apply k-means clustering
set.seed(123) # Ensure reproducibility
kmeans_result <- kmeans(pca_data, centers = 3, nstart = 25) # Adjust 'centers' based on Elbow Method results

# Step 4: Visualize the clusters
fviz_cluster(kmeans_result, data = pca_data,
             geom = "point", ellipse.type = "convex",
             palette = "jco", ggtheme = theme_minimal(),
             main = "Clustering Results in PCA Space")

Elbow Method

  • The Elbow Method plot suggests that the optimal number of clusters is 3. This is where the reduction in the Total Within Sum of Square starts to level off significantly, indicating a balance between compactness and separation.

Cluster Visualization

  • The clustering visualization shows three distinct groups plotted in the PCA-reduced space (first two principal components):

    • Cluster 1 (Blue): This group represents observations with certain shared characteristics in Dim1 and Dim2.

    • Cluster 2 (Yellow): Positioned distinctly, this group differs from Cluster 1 and Cluster 3 based on the PCA dimensions.

    • Cluster 3 (Gray): A separate group indicating unique shared features.

Conclusion:

  1. The clusters are well-separated in the PCA space, suggesting meaningful grouping of the data.

  2. These clusters may represent distinct subgroups within the dataset that differ across health metrics.

6 Part II

6.1 Transform a Categorical Variable

# Transform Outcome into a binary variable with an imbalanced split
data_imputed$BinaryOutcome <- ifelse(data_imputed$Outcome == 1, "Rare", "Common")

# Check the proportion of the two classes
table(data_imputed$BinaryOutcome)

Common   Rare 
   500    268 
prop.table(table(data_imputed$BinaryOutcome))

   Common      Rare 
0.6510417 0.3489583

The output indicates that the transformation of the Outcome variable into a BinaryOutcome was successful, with the following distribution:

  • Common: 500 observations (approximately 65% of the dataset).

  • Rare: 268 observations (approximately 35% of the dataset).

However, the Rare category constitutes more than 10% of the dataset, meaning it does not yet meet the criteria of being the smaller group (<10%).

6.2 Refine the Binary Variable

# Refine the BinaryOutcome based on Outcome and Glucose levels
data_imputed$RefinedBinaryOutcome <- ifelse(data_imputed$Outcome == 1 & data_imputed$Glucose > 140, "Rare", "Common")

# Check the new distribution
table(data_imputed$RefinedBinaryOutcome)

Common   Rare 
   636    132 
prop.table(table(data_imputed$RefinedBinaryOutcome))

  Common     Rare 
0.828125 0.171875 
# Visualize the new BinaryOutcome distribution
ggplot(data_imputed, aes(x = RefinedBinaryOutcome)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "steelblue") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Refined BinaryOutcome", x = "Refined Binary Outcome", y = "Count")

The refined BinaryOutcome variable now has the following distribution:

  • Common: 636 observations (~83% of the dataset).

  • Rare: 132 observations (~17% of the dataset).

This refinement has brought the Rare group closer to the desired threshold (<10%). While still slightly above, the distribution is more imbalanced than before, making it suitable for clustering and PCA analysis.

6.3 PCA for Refined Binary Outcome

# Perform PCA (reuse the standardized data from Part I)
pca_result_refined <- PCA(data_scaled, graph = FALSE)

# Scree plot to check variance explained
fviz_screeplot(pca_result_refined, addlabels = TRUE, 
               title = "Scree Plot: Variance Explained by Principal Components (Refined Outcome)")

# Biplot focusing on variable contributions only
fviz_pca_var(pca_result_refined, 
             col.var = "contrib", # Color by contributions to principal components
             gradient.cols = c("blue", "yellow", "red"), 
             repel = TRUE,       # Avoid overlapping text
             title = "PCA Biplot: Variable Contributions for Refined Outcome")

Scree Plot

  • The first two principal components explain 47.2% of the total variance (28.8% + 18.4%).

  • Including a third component raises the explained variance to 61.3%, similar to Part I.

  • Conclusion: The first two or three components provide sufficient dimensionality reduction for further analysis.

Variable Contributions (Biplot)

  • Dim1 (28.8% variance explained):

    • Strongly influenced by Age and Pregnancies, which contribute most to this dimension.

  • Dim2 (18.4% variance explained):

    • Influenced by BMI, SkinThickness, and Glucose, indicating variability related to body metrics and glucose levels.

  • DiabetesPedigreeFunction contributes uniquely, aligning separately from the other variables, highlighting its distinct role.

Conclusion: The variables influencing the principal components align well with health metrics relevant to the refined binary outcome.

6.4 Clustering Analysis

# Use the first two principal components for clustering
pca_data_refined <- pca_result_refined$ind$coord[, 1:2]

# Determine the optimal number of clusters using the Elbow Method
fviz_nbclust(pca_data_refined, kmeans, method = "wss") + 
  ggtitle("Elbow Method for Optimal Clusters (Refined Outcome)")

# Apply k-means clustering (using 2 clusters as the refined outcome has two categories)
set.seed(123)
kmeans_refined <- kmeans(pca_data_refined, centers = 2, nstart = 25)

# Visualize the clustering results
fviz_cluster(kmeans_refined, data = pca_data_refined,
             geom = "point", ellipse.type = "convex",
             palette = "jco", ggtheme = theme_minimal(),
             main = "Clustering Results for Refined BinaryOutcome")

Elbow Method

  • The Elbow Method plot indicates that 2 clusters is the optimal number, as the elbow point occurs at k=2. This aligns with the fact that the RefinedBinaryOutcome variable has two categories (Common and Rare).

Cluster Visualization

  • The clustering results in the PCA-reduced space show two distinct groups:

    • Cluster 1 (Blue): Likely corresponds to one of the RefinedBinaryOutcome categories (e.g., Common).

    • Cluster 2 (Yellow): Likely corresponds to the other category (e.g., Rare).

6.5 Compare Clusters with Refined Binary Outcome

# Contingency table to compare clustering and RefinedBinaryOutcome
table(data_imputed$RefinedBinaryOutcome, kmeans_refined$cluster)
        
           1   2
  Common 401 235
  Rare    16 116
  1. Cluster 1 (Blue):

  • Primarily consists of Common cases (401 observations).

  • Contains only a small number of Rare cases (16 observations).

  1. Cluster 2 (Yellow):

  • Contains most of the Rare cases (116 observations).

  • Also includes a significant number of Common cases (235 observations).

  • Cluster Purity:

    • Cluster 2 (Yellow) captures a majority of the Rare group (116 out of 132, ~88%).

    • Cluster 1 (Blue) captures a majority of the Common group (401 out of 636, ~63%).

  • Overlap:

    • Some overlap exists, particularly with 235 Common cases falling into Cluster 2.

7 Final Conclusion

Part I: Initial PCA and Clustering

  1. PCA Results:

  • The first two principal components captured 47.2% of the variance, effectively reducing the datasets dimensionality for clustering.

  • Key variables contributing to variability included Age, Pregnancies, BMI, and Glucose.

  1. Clustering Analysis:

  • Using k-means clustering, three distinct clusters were identified in the PCA-reduced space.

  • The clusters suggested natural groupings based on health metrics, aligning well with expectations but without specific labels.

Part II: Binary Variable Transformation and Analysis

  1. Refinement of Binary Outcome:
  • The original Outcome variable was refined using both Glucose levels and diabetic status, resulting in a more imbalanced split (83% Common, 17% Rare).
  1. PCA Results for Refined Outcome:

  • The first two principal components explained the same variance as in Part I (47.2%), with similar variable contributions.

  • Variables such as Age, Pregnancies, and BMI remained influential in defining the principal components.

  1. Clustering and Comparison:

  • Two clusters were identified, aligning well with the RefinedBinaryOutcome categories:

    • Cluster 2 (Yellow) captured 88% of Rare cases, effectively grouping the smaller category.

    • Some overlap occurred, with Common cases present in both clusters.

  • PCA successfully reduced the datasets dimensionality while retaining meaningful information.

  • Clustering provided valuable insights into the natural groupings in the data and aligned well with the refined binary variable.

  • The methods demonstrated the utility of unsupervised learning in identifying patterns in health-related datasets, highlighting differences between groups based on key metrics.
